Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to light them up before the plane reaches an altitude of 10,000 feet and the commander gives its green light.
Passengers are supposed to turn off their aircraft when the plane is down before the landing and do not light them up until the aircraft is set.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-off, landing and ground rolling, FAA said.
Most of the new line planes and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
