How biometry invaded our lives
Finish typing passwords to access his smartphone or pay his purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier , Deputy Director General of Morpho , even estimates that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person performing transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet .
Privacy organizations confirm this enchantment for biometry, but worry about it.
Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for Computer Science and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everybody can soon be identified, anywhere and any time," said Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology), in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometry will be based on new techniques, which will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are the fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some concrete workers have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," notes Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection and verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand imply a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a safety - we cannot capture this data in vain - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore take time.
As a result, research has been carried out over the past 20 years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the ability to calculate the computers needed for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The precision of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the last five years, calculated Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture's R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we are conducting research on the recognition of voice or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible brand, DNA is also a source of hope and concern.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Voretiet-Tavenier, director of studies, innovation and prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a suitcase costing $90,000 to analyze DNA samples at a crime scene and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (to ensure that the person is the one it claims to be).
The identification was currently concerned with the issue of identity papers: the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) must be compared with the information that the state has on all already fixed citizens.
This ensures that one person does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or store.
"We collect images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, responsible for commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a quidam who queues in a store, follow its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (border, protected premises, cellars...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, it has been added to the presence check.
"One pointed biometric avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend that points for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing its card and placing its hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the impact of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and large distribution teachers: at the time of paying in store with its bank card, the client does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
Experimentation is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Hints to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometry attractive to the public.
The first is to explain that she can make time.
"If, thanks to biometry, a customer stays in a box for thirty seconds less, it's appreciable," says the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"Digital fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which blocks if we try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
However, because of the lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy specialists continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me fear the worst: widespread surveillance," predicted Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
