Scientists have just highlighted the way a dog's tail movements are linked to its mood.
Previous studies revealed that happy dogs moved their tails further to the right (from the point of view of the dog), while nerve dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in the stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in man, the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies where other dogs appeared.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will certainly not take long before we understand why their tails sometimes go on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films where other dogs were present – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to prevent any other confusion – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or to the right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression turn the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog that removes the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a tail drifted mainly to the left (once again from the point of view of the dog that removes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think that dogs would communicate deliberately with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react to this experience."
Researchers indicate that results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The canine behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a joyful dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when his tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what was in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could come from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider animals from movies or robots dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tails sometimes move on one side and sometimes on the other.
