And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and as many of his countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed over 700 surgical acts free of charge last year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé's central hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which goes to rural areas during the weekend to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they ride into vans after having fixed the medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to reach villages that need the most help.
