In the evening, the practical team of simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually performed in a school, a city hall or a house; after the intervention, the patient wakes up and goes to the waking room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers worked until early Sunday morning.
It's an irresistible pace, but village musicians generally help the team stay motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so that we can continue to work," said Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work it has done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical acts free of charge in the past year, and knows that their presence can make any difference for those to whom they come to help.
