"We were able to participate in operations to help drain the blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said Miss O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a medical student in the second year.
Voluntary students generally pay for their travel to Cameroon, and often arrive with medical equipment collected.
But once in Yaoundé, their pensions, transportation and education are taken over by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to dying.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
